coli, Manabe shows how climate models have been used as virtual laboratories for examining the complex planetary interactions of atmosphere, ocean, and land. Manabe and Broccoli use these studies as the basis for a broader discussion of human-induced global warming-and what the future may hold for a warming planet. They tell the stories of early trailblazers such as Svante Arrhenius, the legendary Swedish scientist who created the first climate model of Earth more than a century ago, and provide rare insights into Manabe's own groundbreaking work over the past five decades. Expertly walking readers through key breakthroughs, they explain why increasing atmospheric carbon dioxide has caused temperatures to rise in the troposphere yet fall in the stratosphere, why the warming of the planet's surface differs by hemisphere, why drought is becoming more frequent in arid regions despite the global increase in precipitation, and much more.Authoritative and illuminating, Beyond Global Warming is an invaluable insider's look at some of today's most cutting-edge Earth science, and a rare window into a brilliant scientific mind.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aClimatic changesxComputer simulation. 0aClimatic changesxMathematical models. 0aClimatic changesxResearch. 7aSCIENCE / Global Warming & Climate Change.2bisacsh  a3-D general circulation model.  aA Very Short Introduction.  aCO2 concentration.  aCO2.  aClimate Change.  aE. O. Hulbert.  aGCMs.  aGFDL models.  aJean-Baptiste Fourier.  aJohn Tyndall.  aMark Maslin.  aNorman Phillips.  aSpencer R. Weart.  aSvante Arrhenius.  aThe Discovery of Global Warming.  acarbon emissions.  aconservation.  ageneral circulation models.  aglobal warming.  agreenhouse effect.  agreenhouse gasses.  apolar amplification.  aradiative equilibr